<DOC><DOCNO> AP890806-0065 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-08-06-89 2056EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r a AM-HostagePoll     08-06 0306</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Hostage Poll,0314</SECOND><HEAD>Majority Support Negotiations, Oppose Bombing to Free Hostages</HEAD><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Most Americans believe the United States shouldnegotiate with terrorists to free the Middle East hostages andshould refrain from bombing terrorist hideouts in Lebanon,according to a poll released Sunday.   Of the 500 people surveyed in the Time Magazine-Cable NewsNetwork poll, 58 percent support negotiations while 39 percentoppose such talks.   Asked whether they support bombing terrorist hideouts in Lebanonif innocent people might be killed, 60 percent said no, and 33percent said yes.   Seventy-six percent oppose paying ransom for hostages, versus 19percent who approve of the ransom idea.   When asked about sending in commandos to rescue the hostages ona mission that could endanger lives, 50 percent rejected the planand 40 percent supported it.   The respondents were evenly divided on whether the United Statesshould bomb targets in Iran because of Iran's link to the Lebanesekidnappers, with 45 percent supporting such an action and 45percent opposing it.   Forty-six percent approve of the way President Bush has beenhandling the hostage crisis, while 32 percent disapprove.   Asked if Israel was justified in kidnapping Sheik Abdul KarimObeid, only 25 percent said yes; 53 percent said the action wenttoo far.   A fourth of those polled said they believe Israel is partlyresponsible for the death of U.S. Marine Lieut. Colonel WilliamHiggins, but one-half of the respondents said Higgins' Arab captorswere solely to blame for his execution.   Higgins was kidnapped last year while heading an observer teamwith the United Nations peacekeeping force in Lebanon. His captorsclaim they killed him last week in retaliation for Israel'skidnapping of Sheik Obeid.   The poll was conducted Aug. 3 by Yankelovich Clancy Shulman witha sampling error estimated at plus or minus 4.5 percent.</TEXT></DOC>